eCommerce site builder FAQ

What is an eCommerce website?

An eCommerce website is a website from which you can buy or sell physical or digital products online. This can include a digital storefront, product galleries, product pages, an online shopping cart, online checkout, and all of the backend features you need to manage payment processing, shipping, customer support and eCommerce marketing.

What do I need in order to build an eCommerce website?

In order to build an eCommerce website, you need the following:

  1. A domain name - Your domain name, which is your sites unique URL, should reflect your brand.

  2. Hosting - This is the infrastructure on which your website is maintained. You should seek reliable ecommerce hosting that ensures your site maximum uptime.

  3. Products to sell - You can sell your own physical or digital products and services, or sell ready-to-ship products from a dropshipping supplier.

  4. Payment provider - This is a company that enables you to accept payments. Ideally, your payment provider should let you accept multiple payment methods.

  5. Online store theme/template and design - Sign up for an eCommerce website builder that allows you to choose a suitable template and customize it.

With Wix, you can get all of these tools for building an eCommerce website in one place.

Where can I host my eCommerce website?

Wix provides secure and free web hosting as soon as you publish your site, even if its a free e-commerce website without a Premium plan. Combined with Wixs own data centers, your site runs on the unified power of Google Cloud, AWS and Fastly. Your Wix site is served by four data centers across three continents, and is reinforced by over 200 global content delivery network (CDN) nodes. This multi-cloud hosting improves your load times and provides full global coverage.

How can I use AI in e-commerce to increase my website sales?

AI can be used in a number of ways to increase your e-commerce websites reach and revenue. Wix features several AI tools which can help you increase traffic, engagement and sales, including:

  1. AI product description generator - This tool allows you to enter simple prompts about your products and Wix's AI Text Creator will quickly generate high-quality product descriptions, saving time and effort, and uplifting conversion and SEO.

  2. Twik AI-powered site personalization - This smart AI engine shows store visitors a personalized product arrangement tailored to their shopping habits. On average, Twik users see a revenue uplift of 12% after using the app.

  3. Smart product recommendations - You can increase your average order value with AI-based product recommendation sections, displaying related products personalized to your customer before checkout. Algorithms include frequently bought together, bestsellers, and more.

  4. AI image creator - This tool allows you to create personalized image content for your online store by simply providing  a prompt and applying your preferred image style. Having high-quality images on your e-commerce website is a key to increasing sales.

How much does it cost to create an eCommerce website?

The cost of creating an eCommerce website can vary depending on the size of your site, the features you need and whether you hire a professional to design your site or do it yourself on an all-inclusive platform.

When you take into account design costs, the costs of feature plug-ins, hosting costs and domain costs, you can pay anywhere from an estimated $1,000 to over $10,000 to build and maintain an e-Commerce website.

If you opt to build a website on a platform that includes domain, hosting and feature costs, the price will generally be much less. Depending on the platform you choose, and how advanced a plan you need, monthly prices range from about $20 to $200 per month. For example, Wix plans for eCommerce range from $27 to $159 per month.

What types of eCommerce websites are there?

There are several types of eCommerce websites:

  1. eCommerce websites that sell their own physical products - The most common type of store is one that sells its own physical products. Examples of physical products are clothing items, or kitchen accessories. In this type of site, customers pay for their purchases online through the website, and then can either pick up their items in person, or have them shipped to their location.

  2. Dropshipping websites -  While dropshipping websites also sell physical products, the site owner doesnt supply the products themselves. In this case the site features products from a dropshipping supplier. When the customer makes a purchase from the site, the supplier ships the product directly to the customer. The owner doesnt have to hold inventory or handle shipping in dropshipping eCommerce. They merely have to display the products on their site and attract customers. To learn how to start a dropshipping business, check out our blog.

  3. Print-on-demand websites - Print-on-demand is a form of dropshipping eCommerce in which the supplier prints the site owners designs or logo on products such as t-shirts, mugs, or more exotic products like headphones and chefs knives in the case of Wixs native print-on-demand integration. Just as with dropshipping, the supplier handles the shipping and fulfillment to the end customer.

  4. eCommerce websites that sell digital products - Stores that sell digital products sell downloadable or viewable products that do not need to be shipped. This can include ebooks, online courses, music, gift cards, and more.


On a platform such as Wix, you dont have to choose only one of these types of eCommerce sites. In fact, you can offer your own physical and digital products, as well as dropshipping and print-on-demand products all on one site and manage it all from your Wix dashboard.

How do I build an eCommerce website?

Here are 6 simple steps to create your eCommerce site and start to sell products online fast:


1. Choose your platform and plan

Start by picking an eCommerce website builder that includes hosting, security, payments and store management. With Wix, you get all these and its free to start. Upgrade whenever youre ready to begin accepting payments.


2. Plan your eCommerce website design

Decide how you want your store to look and how shoppers will move through it. On Wix you can choose a ready-made store template or use AI to create a custom layout. Then adjust colors, fonts and sections so your design matches your brand.


3. Add your products and store content

Create clear product pages so customers know exactly what theyre buying. Add titles, descriptions, prices and high-quality images. Adjust image sizes or color, manage stock and group items into collections to make browsing and buying easier.


4. Set up payments and checkout

Connect a payment provider so you can accept credit cards and other popular payment methods. Then customize your checkout details, including taxes, shipping options and your store policies (like returns and refunds) so they follow local laws and match how you handle orders.


5. Configure shipping and key store settings

Set shipping regions and rates, offer options like local delivery or pickup if relevant and define handling times. Add your contact details, terms and return policy so shoppers know what to expect when they buy from you.


6. Preview, publish and start selling

Before you go live, test your site on desktop and mobile. Click through product pages, your cart and checkout to make sure everything works smoothly. When it looks right, publish your eCommerce store and use built-in SEO, email marketing and social media features to bring in traffic and sell products online.

Can I integrate PayPal, Stripe or other payment gateways with my Wix eCommerce site?

Yes. You can connect PayPal, Stripe and over 70 other payment providers to your Wix eCommerce site, depending on where your business is based. You can also use Wix Payments, our builtin solution, to accept major credit and debit cards plus digital wallets like Apple Pay and Google Pay.


When you set up your store, you choose which payment methods to offer and connect them in your Wix dashboard. You can even use more than one provider at the same time (for example Wix Payments plus PayPal), so your store can give customers several secure ways to pay at checkout.

How secure are eCommerce platforms for handling customer payments?

Most modern eCommerce platforms are secure for handling customer payments, as long as they follow industry standards and you choose trusted providers.

When you compare platforms or eCommerce software, look for:


  • PCI DSS compliance This is the global security standard for processing credit cards. Your provider should be PCI compliant so you dont have to handle raw card data yourself.

  • HTTPS and SSL encryption Your online store URL should start with https:// and show a lock icon so login details and payment info are encrypted in transit.

  • Secure payment gateways Using trusted providers (like major credit card processors, PayPal and other wellknown gateways) adds extra layers of security and fraud checks.

  • Builtin fraud protection Tools like address and CVV checks and extra authentication (such as 3D Secure where supported) help reduce chargebacks and suspicious orders.

  • Ongoing security maintenance Regular security updates and monitoring for unusual activity are key to keeping customer data safe.


With Wix, your store is protected by builtin SSL encryption and payments processed through PCIcompliant providers, including Wix Payments (where available). Sensitive card data is handled by certified systems and not stored on your site, so you can focus on running your business while we take care of payment security in the background.


Whats the easiest way to calculate taxes on my ecommerce site?

The easiest way to calculate taxes on your eCommerce website is to automate sales tax and VAT based on each customers location. With Wix, you can set up automated tax calculation from your dashboard so the correct rate is applied at checkout, without you having to track changing tax rules or do the math yourself.

To do this, you can:

  • Choose the countries or states where you need to collect tax

  • Let Wix automatically calculate and apply the right rate to eligible orders

  • Set different rules for products that are taxed differently or taxexempt


If you prefer, you can also enter tax rates manually instead of using automation. Wix makes it much easier to handle tax, but you should still check with a tax professional or local authority to confirm where youre required to collect tax before you start selling.
